unced his separation from Barstool Sports on August 31, 2018, citing a lack of transparency with the business operations of the company as his reason for leaving.\n\n===Fox Sports and ESPN===\nOn November 24, 2018, McAfee made his college football broadcasting debut on Fox, calling a college football game between [[Baylor Bears football|Baylor]] and [[Texas Tech Red Raiders football|Texas Tech]]. On December 30, McAfee made his NFL broadcasting debut on Fox, joining [[Justin Kutcher]], Robert Smith, and sideline reporter [[Sarah Kustok]] for the [[2018 Detroit Lions season|Lions]]\u2013[[2018 Green Bay Packers season|Packers]] game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prideofdetroit.com/2018/12/27/18157697/pat-mcafee-making-nfl-broadcasting-debut-lions-packers-week-17/|title=Former Colts punter Pat McAfee making NFL broadcasting debut for Lions vs. Packers|date=December 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn July 29, 2019, [[Adam Schefter]] announced via Twitter that McAfee would be joining ESPN as the [[Color commentator|color analyst]] for their ''[[ESPN College Football Thursday Primetime|Thursday Night College Football]]'' broadcasts, alongside [[Matt Hasselbeck]]. Also, McAfee will be making regular weekly appearances on ''[[Get Up! (TV program)|Get Up!]]''. This news comes after McAfee had auditioned for on ESPN's ''[[Monday Night Football]]'' after [[Jason Witten]]'s return to the Cowboys, though ESPN decided to retain its booth as-is.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.si.com/tech-media/2019/07/29/pat-mcafee-joins-espn-college-football-color-analyst|title=Pat McAfee joins ESPN as college football color analyst|website=SI.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> McAfee began making regular appearances on ESPN's [[College GameDay (football TV program)|College GameDay]] in 2019.\n\n===DAZN and Westwood One ===\nOn August 7, 2019, it was reported that McAfee would begin to host a two-hour, weekday radio show, ''The Pat McAfee Show'', beginning September 9, 2019, syndicated by [[Westwood One]] and [[DAZN]]. The deal with DAZN also includes McAfee streaming his podcast on the service three times per-week, and appearances in NFL-related shoulder content in regions where DAZN holds streaming rights to the league (primarily Canada and Germany).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/nfl-star-pat-mcafee-lands-daily-show-dazn-westwoodone-1229887|title=Former NFL Star Pat McAfee Lands Daily Show on DAZN and Westwood One (Exclusive)|work=The Hollywood Reporter|first=Marisa|last=Guthrie|date=August 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com:443/en/Journal/Issues/2019/09/16/Media/Sports%20media.aspx|title=Party time: How DAZN, Westwood One got McAfee|last=September 16|last2=2019|website=www.sportsbusinessdaily.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref>\n\n===Other appearances===\nMcAfee is a regular on the nationally syndicated morning radio program ''[[The Bob & Tom Show]]'', itself based in Indianapolis. He has described co-host [[Bob Kevoian]] as one of his best friends during an interview on the ''Off the Air Podcast'' hosted by sports commentator [[Chick McGee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chickmcgee.com/2015/02/10/episode-128-pat-mcafee-returns/|title=Episode 128: Pat McAfee Returns|work=Off the Air Podcast|date=February 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, McAfee made his professional baseball debut for the [[Washington Wild Things]] as a right-fielder and guest first base coach. He made a [[putout]] in the outfield and went 0-3 at the plate, reaching second base on a throwing error before being replaced with a [[pinch runner]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Pat McAfee: Professional Baseball Player|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U-OBaprDBSk|language=en|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref>\n\nHe became a sideline reporter for the [[XFL (2020)|XFL]] in its inaugural season in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inquirer.com/sports/xfl-rules-game-time-channel-stream-vince-mcmahon-announcers-abc-espn-fox-20200208.html|title=The XFL lasted just one season back in 2001. Can it do better this time?|last=Tornoe|first=Rob|date=|website=Philadelphia Inquirer|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n===In-ring endeavors===\nA month before the [[2009 NFL Draft|NFL Draft]], on March 22, 2009, McAfee was involved in a match against The WarPig at an IWA East Coast show in [[South Charleston, West Virginia]]. WarPig controlled much of the match, but McAfee hit him with a low blow and a super kick, securing an upset victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.wvgazettemail.com/popcult/2009/03/23/pat-mcafee-in-the-ring-the-popcult-instant-mini-photo-essay/|title=Pat McAfee In The Ring: The PopCult Instant Mini Photo Essay|work=Charleston Gazette-Mail|first=Rudy|last=Panucci|date=March 23, 2009|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref> In March 2018, McAfee was present at an [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]] show in Indianapolis, where he prevented [[Adam Cole]] from winning by DQ in his match against [[Aleister Black]]. Instead, McAfee's distraction was enough time for Black to recover and hit Cole with his finisher, ''Black Mass''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indystar.com/story/news/2018/03/05/pat-mcafee-steals-show-settles-beef-adam-cole-wwe-nxt/394476002/|title=Pat McAfee steals the show, settles beef with Adam Cole at WWE NXT|work=Indianapolis Star|first=Justin L.|last=Mack|date=March 5, 2019|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Analyst work with WWE===\nDuring 2018, McAfee began appearing on [[WWE]] programming as a pre-show analyst for the companies' [[NXT Takeover]] events, beginning with [[NXT TakeOver: New Orleans]], where he continued his mini-feud with Adam Cole. He later appeared at [[NXT TakeOver: Chicago II]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-results/nxt-takeover-chicago-live-results-gargano-vs-ciampa-street-fight-259781|title=NXT TAKEOVER CHICAGO LIVE RESULTS: GARGANO VS. CIAMPA STREET FIGHT|work=Wrestling Observer Newsletter|first=Chris|last=Aiken|date=June 16, 2018|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref> [[NXT TakeOver: Brooklyn 4]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-results/nxt-takeover-brooklyn-iv-live-results-ciampa-vs-gargano-264031|title=NXT TAKEOVER BROOKLYN IV LIVE RESULTS: CIAMPA VS. GARGANO|work=Wrestling Observer Newsletter|first=Chris|last=Aiken|date=August 18, 2018|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref> and [[NXT TakeOver: WarGames (2018)|NXT TakeOver: WarGames]]. In December, it was reported that he had formally signed a multi-year contract with WWE,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/wrestling/2018/12/28/former-colts-punter-pat-mcafee-signs-wwe-contract|title=Former Colts Punter Pat McAfee Signs Multi-Year Contract With WWE|work=Sports Illustrated|first=Emily|last=Caron|date=December 28, 2018|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref> and officially signed the contract in February 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/article/pat-mcafee-signs-with-wwe|title=Pat McAfee signs as contributor with WWE|publisher=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=February 7, 2019|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.wvgazettemail.com/popcult/2019/02/07/wvu-great-and-iwa-east-coast-wrestler-pat-mcafee-joins-wwe/|title=WVU Great And IWA East Coast Wrestler Pat McAfee Joins WWE|work=Charleston Gazette-Mail|first=Rudy|last=Panucci|date=February 7, 2019|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref> He then began hosting live watch-along of WWE's pay-per-views on [[YouTube]], beginning with [[Fastlane (2019)|Fastlane]], alongside a number of WWE wrestlers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/first-wwe-watch-along-stream-social-media-during-fastlane-278721|title=FIRST WWE WATCH ALONG TO STREAM ON SOCIAL MEDIA DURING FASTLANE|work=Wrestling Observer Newsletter|first=Joseph|last=Currier|date=March 7, 2019|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref> In the buildup to [[WrestleMania 35|WrestleMania]], McAfee, his crew and various special guests travelled venue to venue in an RV, which was filmed for ''Pat McAfee's Road to WrestleMania''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prowrestling.com/watch-pat-mcafee-joined-by-wwe-superstars-on-the-road-to-wrestlemania/|title=Watch: Pat McAfee Joined By WWE Superstars On The Road To WrestleMania Backstage|work=ProWrestling.com|first=Matthew|last=Wilkinson|date=April 4, 2019|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref> Backstage at the event, McAfee got into an argument with [[Michael Cole (wrestling)|Michael Cole]], when Cole had criticised him for wearing tuxedo shorts. McAfee threatened to quit on the spot, and was sent to another room while the situation was dealt with. After [[Vince McMahon]] was shown an image of [[LeBron James]] at the [[2018 NBA Finals]], and that the outfit was similar to the one McAfee was wearing for WrestleMania, McMahon approved and McAfee was allowed to co-host the second hour of the pre-show, alongside Charly Caruso.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indystar.com/story/news/2019/04/11/pat-mcafee-wrestlemania-tuxedo-shorts-almost-cost-him-his-wwe-job/3433203002/|title=Pat McAfee almost quit his WWE dream job moments before WrestleMania over tuxedo shorts|work=Indianapolis Star|first=Justin L.|last=Mack|date=April 12, 2019|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMcAfee made a guest appearance on the November 1, 2019 edition of ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown]]'', as part of an on-air staff filling in for Cole and Graves (who were not able to make it back from [[Crown Jewel (2019)|Crown Jewel]] on time), where McAfee fully supported [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]]'s invasion of the show, and ultimately stormed the ring alongside the rest of the ''NXT'' roster at the end of the broadcast as they declared war on both [[WWE Raw (brand)|Raw]] and [[WWE SmackDown (brand)|SmackDown]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/friday-smackdown-announcers-renee-young-tom-phillips-aiden-english-wwe-saudi-arabia-delay/|title=WWE Sets Announcers for 'SmackDown' in Wake of Saudi Arabia Delays|date=2019-11-01|website=TheWrap|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wrestlinginc.com/news/2019/11/special-wwe-smackdown-announce-team-revealed-for-tonight-661587/|title=Special WWE SmackDown Announce Team Revealed For Tonight, Update On The WWE Travel Situation|work=[[Wrestling Inc.]]|date=November 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fightful.com/wrestling/shayna-baszler-matt-riddle-keith-lee-appear-wwe-smackdown|title=Shayna Baszler, Matt Riddle, Keith Lee Appear On WWE SmackDown &#124; Fightful Wrestling|website=www.fightful.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/nxt-invasion-takes-place-wwe-smackdown-296371|title=NXT invasion takes place on WWE SmackDown|date=November 1, 2019|website=WON/F4W - WWE news, Pro Wrestling News, WWE Results, UFC News, UFC results}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\n[[File:Pat McAfee Indianapolis Colts punter, visits Camp Atterbury 120724-A-IB445-002.jpg|thumb|McAfee visits [[Camp Atterbury]] with Wish for Our Heroes in 2012]]\nThe Pat McAfee Foundation is a not-for-profit organization with the goal of providing assistance for the sons and daughters of military personnel. McAfee worked closely with his father, Tim McAfee, to establish the foundation.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us-History|url=http://www.thepatmcafeefoundation.com/about-us/history/|publisher=Pat McAfee Foundation|accessdate=January 1, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120514000446/http://www.thepatmcafeefoundation.com/about-us/history/|archivedate=May 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, McAfee created a company named Shirts for America, to serve as a sponsor for [[Indycar Series|Indycar]] driver [[Conor Daly]] for the [[2016 Indianapolis 500]] and to support both the Pat McAfee Foundation and Wish for Our Heroes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pat McAfee founds company Shirts for America to sponsor Conor Daly in Indy 500|url=http://www.wthr.com/story/32003737/pat-mcafee-set-to-make-big-indy-500-announcement|publisher=WHTR|accessdate=May 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, McAfee chopped off his signature locks for [[Locks of Love]], an organization that provides hairpieces for children who are suffering from long-term illness and are poor.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chapman|first=Chuck|title=Pat McAfee Sheds Ponytail for Charity|url=http://www.colts101.com/2011/11/26/pat-mcafee-sheds-pony-tail-for-charity/|publisher=Sports Media 101|accessdate=January 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn October 20, 2010, McAfee was arrested and charged with public intoxication, a Class B misdemeanor. McAfee had been found shirtless and wet, and alleged to have swam in a canal in [[Broad Ripple]], a popular nightclub area, at approximately 5:15 that morning after being reported by a woman who found him near her car. Police reported that he tested with a blood alcohol content of 0.15.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theindychannel.com/sports/25449750/detail.html|title=Colts' McAfee Suspended After Public Intoxication Arrest|work=theindychannel.com|date=October 21, 2010|accessdate=July 23, 2014}}</ref> The Colts later issued a one-game suspension to McAfee for his actions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indystar.com/article/20101022/NEWS02/310220007/1003/BUSINESS/Colts-punter-Pat-McAfee-charged-with-misdemeanor|title=Colts punter Pat McAfee charged with misdemeanor - IndyStar.com|publisher=}}</ref> Two weeks after being arrested, McAfee issued an apology for his actions. \"Obviously I made a dumb decision on a night when things got out of control,\" he said. \"I will never put my team or my family through this kind of embarrassment again.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Colts punter Pat McAfee apologizes for 'embarrassing' arrest|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/colts/2010-11-03-pat-mcafee_N.htm|publisher=USA Today | date=November 3, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn February 5, 2016, McAfee became a [[Guinness World Records|Guinness World Record]] holder by successfully kicking a 40-yard field goal while blindfolded.<ref>{{cite web|last1=daSilva|first1=Cameron|title=Colts' Pat McAfee sets Guinness World Record for longest blindfolded FG|url=http://www.foxsports.com/nfl/story/indianapolis-colts-pat-mcafee-guinness-world-record-blindfolded-field-goal-020516/|website=Fox Sports|accessdate=February 16, 2016}}</ref> The record was surpassed two years later when Davis Brief, a fan of McAfee's, kicked a 45-yard field goal while blindfolded on September 23, 2018.<ref>https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/412692-farthest-blindfolded-american-football-field-goal/</ref>\n\nMcAfee became engaged to his girlfriend, Samantha Ludy, in February 2019.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ex-Colts punter Pat McAfee's marriage proposal includes waterfall, helicopter|url=https://www.ajc.com/news/colts-punter-pat-mcafee-marriage-proposal-includes-waterfall-helicopter/Tibqym69DZZs7hsdv9IqeN/|publisher=Atlanta Journal Constitution | date=February 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://patmcafeeshow.com/}}\n\n{{WWE personnel}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McAfee, Pat}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Allegheny County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:West Virginia Mountaineers football players]]\n[[Category:American football placekickers]]\n[[Category:American football punters]]\n[[Category:Indianapolis Colts players]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Unconferenced Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:American Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling announcers]]\n[[Category:XFL (2020) broadcasters]]\n[[Category:National Football League announcers]]\n[[Category:College football announcers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football analyst, professional wrestling analyst, podcaster, small business owner, and retired American football punter.}}\n{{Use American English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name        = Pat McAfee\n| image       = Pat McAfee.JPG\n| image_size  = 200\n| alt         = No.1 Indianapolis Colts\n| caption     = McAfee with the Colts in 2014\n| number      = 1\n| position    = [[Punter (football)|Punter]]\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1987|5|2|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]]\n| height_ft   = 6\n| height_in   = 1\n| weight_lbs  = 233\n| high_school = [[Plum High School|Plum (PA)]]\n| college     = [[West Virginia Mountaineers football|West Virginia]]\n| draftyear   = 2009\n| draftround  = 7\n| draftpick   = 222\n| pastteams   = \n* [[Indianapolis Colts]] ({{NFL Year|2009}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2016}})\n| highlights  = \n* 2\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2015 Pro Bowl|2014]], [[2017 Pro Bowl|2016]])\n* First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2014 All-Pro Team|2014]])\n* [[PFWA All-Rookie Team]] (2009)\n* First-team [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[2008 College Football All-America Team|2008]])\n| statlabel1 = Punts\n| statvalue1 = 575\n| statlabel2 = Punting yards\n| statvalue2 = 26,669\n| statlabel3 = Punting average\n| statvalue3 = 46.4\n| statlabel4 = Longest punt\n| statvalue4 = 74\n| statlabel5 = Inside 20\n| statvalue5 = 193\n| nfl        = MCA385008\n| pfr        = M/McAfPa44\n}}\n'''Patrick Justin McAfee''' (born May 2, 1987) is an American sports analyst, podcaster, and retired [[American football|football]] [[Punter (football)|punter]] who should come out of retirement to join [[Tom Brady]] and [[Rob Gronkowski]] as a [[Tampa Bay Buccaneer]]. He was a [[placekicker]] at [[West Virginia Mountaineers football|West Virginia]] and was drafted by the [[Indianapolis Colts]] in the seventh round of the [[2009 NFL Draft]]. Over his eight-year career in the [[National Football League]] (NFL), McAfee made two [[Pro Bowl]]s and was an [[All-Pro]] in 2014.\n\nSince his retirement from football in February 2017, McAfee has been an analyst in football and professional wrestling. He guested for Fox Sports' college and NFL broadcasts in late 2018, before being announced as part of ESPN's ''[[ESPN College Football Thursday Primetime|Thursday Night College Football]]'' team in July 2019. He also guested for WWE's [[NXT TakeOver]] events during 2018, before signing a contract in February 2019, where he is being primarily used for live watch-alongs of the companies' pay-per-views. McAfee is also a [[stand-up comedian]], and has performed in events around [[Indiana]], and runs his own daily podcast show.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bream|first1=Rebecca|title=Pat McAfee making Indiana comedy tour|url=http://www.indystar.com/story/sports/nfl/colts/2016/01/06/mcafee-making-indiana-comedy-tour/78379410/|website=Indy Star|publisher=USA Today|accessdate=February 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Football career==\n====High school====\nMcAfee attended [[Plum High School]] in his hometown of [[Plum, Pennsylvania]], playing both [[soccer]] and football. As a senior, he borrowed $100 from a friend and played [[poker]] at an illegal club, turning it into $1,400. He used the funds to finance a trip to Miami to participate in the final day of a national competition highlighting the best [[field goal]] kicking prospects in America. McAfee made nine consecutive field goals, starting at 25 yards and moving five yards out each time. He narrowly missed a 70-yard field goal, with the ball missing to the right but with enough distance to make it. After returning home, he was approached in the school's lunchroom by Tony Gibson, [[West Virginia Mountaineers football|West Virginia]]'s recruiting coordinator, who offered him a scholarship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indystar.com/story/sports/nfl/colts/2014/10/24/how-pat-mcafee-became-an-nfl-punter/17815397/|title=$100, a lie and a poker club: How Pat McAfee became an NFL punter|last=Keefer|first=Zak|work=indystar.com|date=October 24, 2014|accessdate=October 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====College career====\n;Freshman season 2005\nMcAfee earned the starting job at [[2005 West Virginia Mountaineers football team|West Virginia]] as a freshman. He was 11-for-18 as a freshman on field goals, and had 70 kickoffs for the season with 20 being touchbacks. McAfee's most memorable moment came against [[2005 Louisville Cardinals football team|Louisville]] in a 46\u201344 triple overtime win, which was reached after a successful McAfee onside kick. The onside kick gave running back [[Steve Slaton]] the chance to tie the game with a one-yard touchdown run.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msnsportsnet.com/profile.cfm?id=101035|title=MSNsportsNET.Com - West Virginia University Mountaineers|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n;Sophomore season 2006\nAlthough they had losses to [[2006 Louisville Cardinals football team|Louisville]] and [[2006 South Florida Bulls football team|USF]], the [[2006 West Virginia Mountaineers football team|Mountaineers]] won ten games and were victors in the [[2006 Gator Bowl|Gator Bowl]] over [[2006 Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football team|Georgia Tech]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msnsportsnet.com/page.cfm?story=10257|title=MSNsportsNET.Com - West Virginia University Mountaineers|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n;Junior season 2007\nMcAfee started his junior season with a missed extra point against [[2007 Western Michigan Broncos football team|Western Michigan]], ending his streak of 106 consecutive extra points. He finished the season in the [[2008 Fiesta Bowl|Fiesta Bowl]] with a 2 for 4 performance, having one kick blocked by [[2007 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma]]. He was named to the ESPN All-Bowl Team following the bowl season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/flash/2007/allbowl|title=ESPN.com's 2007 All-Bowl Football Team|website=sports.espn.go.com}}</ref>\n\nMcAfee missed two relatively short field goals in [[2007 West Virginia Mountaineers football team|WVU's]] [[2007 Backyard Brawl|13\u20139 loss]] to a [[2007 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|Pitt Panthers team]] with only 4 wins; ultimately taking the Mountaineers out of the BCS National Championship Game. He was named to the 2007 [[Lou Groza Award]] semi-finalist list for the best collegiate kicker. McAfee earned Big East Special Team Player of the week honors three times in 2007 and was named second-team All-Big East. He earned West Virginia's Scott Shirley Award for the second consecutive year.\n\n;Senior season 2008\nMcAfee began his [[2008 West Virginia Mountaineers football team|senior year]] in a 48\u201321 season-opening victory over [[Villanova Wildcats football|Villanova]] in which he kicked two field goals, including a career-long of 52-yards, six extra points, and two punts. In the following 27\u20133 win over [[2008 Marshall Thundering Herd football team|Marshall]], McAfee became the school record holder for all-time scoring with a field goal, passing Slaton. He went two for two on field goals to move to third place for the Big East record of career field goals made in a 34\u201317 victory over [[2008 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]].\n\nAgainst [[2008 Cincinnati Bearcats football team|Cincinnati]] on November 8, the Mountaineers trailed by 13 points with 1:11 left in regulation, but reduced the deficit to 3 points with a safety, touchdown, and two-point conversion, all in less than a minute. McAfee's onside kick was recovered with 18 seconds remaining. He then tied the game as time expired with a 52-yard field goal, but the Mountaineers would lose in overtime.\n\nMcAfee finished his senior year with a career-best 44.7 yards per punt average, a Big East-leading 23 punts inside the 20-yard line, and a career-high 2,639 yards with a 65-yard long.\n\n===Professional career===\n;Pre-draft\nAfter his senior season at WVU, McAfee was invited to the 2009 [[Senior Bowl]] in [[Alabama]], joining Mountaineers [[Pat White (American football)|Pat White]] and [[Ellis Lankster]]. He started the Senior Bowl as the South team's kicker. McAfee performed in the 11th annual [[State Farm]] [[College Football All-Star Challenge]], winning the \"round the world\" kicking competition. As he was not invited to the [[NFL Scouting Combine|NFL Combine]], he had team workouts with [[Indianapolis Colts]], [[Dallas Cowboys]] and [[New England Patriots]], all as a kicker.<ref>{{Citation|last=Jose|title=Pat McAfee: Uncaged Part 2|date=July 16, 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TzV_P_M3eSY|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n;Indianapolis Colts\nMcAfee was drafted in the seventh round (222nd overall) of the [[2009 NFL Draft]] by the [[Indianapolis Colts]]. McAfee was signed before training camp. He handled punting and kick-off duties for the Colts in 2009, as well as holding for extra-points and field goals, a position he never played before. In 2009 McAfee helped Indianapolis win the AFC South, the AFC Championship, and helped the Colts reach Super Bowl XLIV.\n\nMcAfee maintained a 46.6-yard punting average for the 2011 regular season, a career-high mark. He would better that mark the following season by posting a 48.2-yard average on punts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/player/patmcafee/89872/profile |title=Pat McAfee, P for the Indianapolis Colts |work=NFL.com |accessdate=March 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn January 4, 2014, McAfee tweeted a photo with Colts teammate [[Andrew Luck]] in the background, almost completely nude.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap2000000311348/article/pat-mcafee-fined-for-posting-andrew-luck-in-the-buff|title=Pat McAfee fined for posting Andrew Luck in the buff|last=Hanzus|first=Dan|work=NFL.com|date=January 9, 2014|accessdate=January 11, 2014}}</ref> McAfee, who was taking a picture of kicker [[Adam Vinatieri]] being interviewed in the locker room, apologized for the incident and was fined $10,000 by the Colts organization, according to his interview with ''[[The Bob & Tom Show]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/bobandtom/pat-mcafee-explains-his-tweet|title=NFL punter Pat McAfee Explains His Tweet|publisher=}}</ref> On March 7, McAfee announced he had signed a five-year contract to remain with the Colts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fansided.com/2014/03/07/pat-mcafee-indianapolis-colts-agree-five-year-deal/ |title=Pat McAfee, Indianapolis Colts agree to five-year deal |last=Sanchez |first=Josh |work=fansided.com |date=March 7, 2014 |accessdate=March 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nMcAfee was named the AFC Special Teams Player of the Month for September 2014. He led the NFL in punting average (45.6 yards) and touchbacks on kickoff (24), and converted the NFL's only two successful onside kicks in the first four weeks of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wthr.com/story/26687482/2014/10/02/colts-pat-mcafee-named-afc-special-teams-player-of-the-month|title=Colts' Pat McAfee named AFC Special Teams Player of the Month|work=wthr.com|date=October 2, 2014|accessdate=October 2, 2014}}</ref> In week 6, McAfee converted his third onside kick of the season, recovering the ball himself after it traveled the necessary 10 yards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2014/10/pat-mcafee-onside-kick|title=The Colts completely fooled the Texans with an early onside kick |last=Mandell |first=Nina |work=ftw.usatoday.com |date=October 9, 2014 |accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref> On December 23, 2014, McAfee was selected to play in his first [[Pro Bowl]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/probowl/story/0ap3000000448746/article/2015-pro-bowl-complete-roster |title=2015 Pro Bowl: Complete roster |work=NFL.com |date=December 23, 2014 |accessdate=December 23, 2014}}</ref> and on January 2, 2015, he was selected by the [[Associated Press]] as the First Team [[All-Pro]] punter.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000452986/article/2014-allpro-teams |title=2014 All-Pro Teams: Analysis of the full rosters |last=Wesseling |first=Chris |work=nfl.com |date=January 2, 2015 |accessdate=January 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn December 20, 2016, McAfee was named to his second Pro Bowl.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indystar.com/story/sports/nfl/colts/2016/12/20/ty-hilton-pat-mcafee-colts-named-pro-bowl/95658362/ |title=T.Y. Hilton, Pat McAfee of the Colts named to Pro Bowl |last=Horner |first=Scott |work=indystar.com |date=December 20, 2016 |accessdate=December 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn February 2, 2017, after eight seasons, McAfee retired from the NFL and stated he intended to join [[Barstool Sports]] as a contributor. He cited his recent knee operation (his third in four seasons) as a factor in his decision, as well as his fractured relationship with Colts' general manager [[Ryan Grigson]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxsports.com/nfl/story/pat-mcafee-retires-joins-barstool-sports-colts-020217|title=Colts punter Pat McAfee retires from NFL to join Barstool Sports {{!}} FOX Sports|date=February 2, 2017|newspaper=FOX Sports|language=en-US|access-date=February 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2018/09/05/pat-mcafee-ryan-grigson-fining-me-for-an-instagram-post-led-to-my-retirement/|title=Pat McAfee: Ryan Grigson fining me for an Instagram post led to my retirement|publisher=Pro Football Talk|first=Michael David|last=Smith|date=September 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n! colspan=\"2\"|Legend\n|-\n| style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"| \n|Led the league\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n|Career high\n|}\n\n====Regular season====\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center;\"\n ! rowspan=2|Season !! rowspan=2|Team !! colspan=16| Punting\n|-\n! {{abbr|GP|Games played}} !! Punts !! {{abbr|Yds|Yards}} !! Net Yds !! {{abbr|Lng|Long punt}} !! {{abbr|Avg|Average}} !! Net Avg !! {{abbr|Blk|Blocked punts}} !! {{abbr|OOB|Out of bounds}} !! {{abbr|Dn|Downed punts}} !! {{abbr|In 20|Inside 20 yard line}} !! {{abbr|TB|Touchbacks}} !! {{abbr|FC|Fair c