er\"\n| 3 || Texas A&M || 1268\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 4 || Auburn || 1090 (1)\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 5 || Mississippi State || 769 (1)\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 6 || Ole Miss || 504\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 7 || Arkansas || 343\n|}\n{{col-2-of-2}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- align=\"center\"\n|align=\"center\" Colspan=\"3\" |'''Media poll (SEC Championship)'''\n|- align=\"center\"\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Alabama Crimson Tide|Rank|Team|Votes}}\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 1 || '''Alabama''' || 209\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 2 || Georgia || 49\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 3 || LSU || 3\n|- align=\"center\"\n| rowspan=\"5\" |4 || Auburn || 1\n|- align=\"center\"\n| Florida || 1\n|- align=\"center\"\n| Mississippi State || 1\n|- align=\"center\"\n| South Carolina || 1\n|- align=\"center\"\n| Tennessee || 1\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Preseason All-SEC teams===\nThe Crimson Tide had 13 players at 14 positions selected to the preseason all-SEC teams.\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n'''Offense'''\n\n''1st team''\n\n[[Tua Tagovailoa]] \u2013 QB\n\n[[Najee Harris]] \u2013 RB\n\n[[Jerry Jeudy]] \u2013 WR\n\nAlex Leatherwood \u2013 OL\n\nJedrick Wills Jr. \u2013 OL\n\n''2nd team''\n\nJaylen Waddle \u2013 WR\n\n''3rd team''\n\nMiller Forristall \u2013 TE\n\nMatt Womack \u2013 OL\n{{col-break}}\n'''Defense'''\n\n''1st team''\n\n[[Raekwon Davis]] \u2013 DL\n\nAnfernee Jennings \u2013 LB\n\n[[Dylan Moses]] \u2013 LB\n\nTrevon Diggs \u2013 DB\n\n''2nd team''\n\n[[Patrick Surtain II]] \u2013 DB\n\n[[Xavier McKinney]] \u2013 DB\n\n''3rd team''\n\nLaBryan Ray  \u2013 DL\n\nTerrell Lewis \u2013 LB\n\nShyheim Carter \u2013 DB\n\n{{col-break}}\n'''Specialists'''\n\n''1st team''\n\nJaylen Waddle \u2013 all purpose player\n\nJaylen Waddle \u2013 RET\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Schedule==\nAlabama announced its 2019 football schedule on September 18, 2018. The 2019 Crimson Tide' schedule consists of 7 home games, 4 away games, and 1 neutral site game for the regular season. Alabama will host four SEC conference opponents [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]] ([[Alabama\u2013Ole Miss football rivalry|rivalry]]), [[Arkansas Razorbacks football|Arkansas]], [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]] ([[Alabama\u2013Tennessee football rivalry|Third Saturday of October]]) and [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] ([[Alabama\u2013LSU football rivalry|rivalry]]) and will travel for four SEC opponents to [[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]], [[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M]], [[Mississippi State Bulldogs football|Mississippi State]] ([[Alabama\u2013Mississippi State football rivalry|rivalry]]) and arch-rival [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]] for the 84th [[Alabama\u2013Auburn football rivalry|Iron Bowl]] to close out the SEC regular season on the road. Alabama is not scheduled to play SEC East opponents [[Florida Gators football|Florida]], [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]], [[Kentucky Wildcats football|Kentucky]], [[Missouri Tigers football|Missouri]] and [[Vanderbilt Commodores football|Vanderbilt]] in the 2019 regular season. The Crimson Tide\u2019s bye week comes during week 6 (on October 5) and week 10 (on November 2).\n\nAlabama's out of conference opponents represent the ACC, C-USA, Independents and Southern. The Crimson Tide will host three non\u2013conference games which are against [[New Mexico State Aggies football|New Mexico State]] of the [[NCAA Division I FBS independent schools|FBS independents]], [[Southern Miss Golden Eagles football|Southern Miss]] of the [[Conference USA]] and  [[Western Carolina Catamounts football|Western Carolina]] of the [[Southern Conference|SoCon]] to close out the regular season and travel to [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta, GA]] for [[Chick-fil-A Kickoff Game|Chick-fil-A Kickoff]] to host [[Duke Blue Devils football|Duke]] from the [[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]].\n\n{{CFB schedule\n| opprank = y\n| rankyear = 2019\n| rankdivision = NCAA Division I FBS\n| poll = [[2019 NCAA Division I FBS football rankings#AP Poll|AP Poll]] 